<<<<
Hello David and Manoj,

I attach four files, containing documentation describing all the code 
updates I made to include the new 1-D target temperature time-dependent 
model. I also included Roth's latest chemical sputtering formula from 
the 11th EFPZ in Heraklion, and generalized the use of 
'nesepm_overshoot' for flux feedback BCs from the core or the PFR 
boundaries.

The fourth file 'platemodel.doc' is a long text file (not Word!) with a 
file-by-file listing of changes.
The first file is an example of a B2PLOT command file that shows some of 
the new capabilities.
The second file is the output from the first one.
The third file is a comparison of the values of the heat conductivity 
for Graphite used in the 0-D model (the 1/(AT+B) formulation) and the 
1-D model (the polynomial fit). I would feel more comfortable if they 
were closer together! Manoj, can you please comment on this and maybe 
suggest new fitting coefficients for either or both sets? Maybe we could 
get an analytic 0-D solution using the polynomial fit so we don4t ask 
for two fits?

As far as Roth's formula is concerned, it basically makes the chemical 
sputtering yield go down at about 1000K instead of 800K but steepens the 
flux dependency at low and intermediate fluxes. This means that one sees 
a small decrease of the chemical sputtering yield at constant flux, and 
an increase at mid-range temperatures. The effect is however somewhat 
marginal on B2 runs, with the possible exception of the consequences of 
moving slightly the location of maximum chemical sputtering.

The files can be found in:
/afs/ipp/u/xpb/solps5.0_drifts/src/Braams/b2/src.local/
/afs/ipp/u/xpb/solps5.0_drifts/data.local/
/afs/ipp/u/xpb/solps5.0_drifts/src/bin.local/common/

Please note that once we try to combine this with Eirene, the mod_wall.F 
file may need to move up to $SOLPSTOP/src/include and need some 
modifications.

The issue of logarithmic spacing of the target 'slices' remains.

The code can become significantly more unstable because of the thermal 
evaporation term, which shoots up even faster than volume recombination. 
I have met such crashes for most JET high-power cases I ran. I got away 
from it by setting the plate thickness to 0.0 (the default) which 
bypasses the whole target temperature model and sets the target surface 
temperature to 'b2stbr_plate_temp', which usually means the cool end 
temperature, in my case 400K. Other ways around it are to turn the 
thermal evaporation term off, by setting 'b2stbr_therm_evap' to '0.0' in 
b2mn.dat, or by setting the vaporization temperature low enough that the 
maximum sublimation rate reached is not lethal. The latter can be done 
by explicit tweaking of the 'Surface_properties.C' data file or in the 
'b2.wall_save.parameters' namelist.

Cheers,

Xavier.
