large number of changes from Xavier:

			      ..ooOOoo..

Subject: New PSI features in B2.5
Date: Wed, 12 Feb 2003 17:38:01 +0100
From: Xavier Bonnin <xpb@ipp.mpg.de>
Organization: Max-Planck-Institut fuer Plasmaphysik
To: David Coster TOK <dpc@ipp.mpg.de>, d.reiter@fz-juelich.de,
hoganjt@ornl.gov
CC: mow@ipp.mpg.de, rfs@ipp.mpg.de

Hello Dave,

Here's some more detail on what Manoj and I have been up to. We have
implemented the following:
- An empirical physical sputtering yield formula that can be used when
TRIM data is unavailable or not desired. The physical dependencies of
the empirical formula are also used when extrapolating TRIM data at low
and high energies.
- An empirical formula for the chemical sputtering yield, which can be
used instead of the constant model with low-energy cut-off we used to
have.
- An empirical formula for RES (Radiation Enhanced Sublimation).
- An empirical formula for thermal evaporation of the plate material.
- The ability in b2plot and through scripts to diagnose these processes.
- A systematic use (at the East and West boundaries) of the sheath
potential computed by the code, used instead of the simple 3.0*Te
estimate (also used for the default chemical sputtering cut-off formula).
- Inclusion in the energy sources of the thermal energy carried back by
the sputtered or evaporated carbon. Also, when TRIM data is present, use
of the "??.ye" tables to get the fraction of the incident energy carried
back into the plasma. If the "??.ye" is not present, the sputtered
particles are considered to come back cold (this can be changed to them
having thermal energy at the plates). Recycled neutrals also carry back
into the plasma at least the thermal energy they were born with (should
help avoid ice-cold plasmas).
- Computation of a surface temperature for each plate mesh element,
using a simple 1-D diffusion model, assuming a user-given plate
thickness and coolant temperature. This is needed for computing all
processes above (except physical sputtering for now).

The empirical formulae are quite detailed and complex, and include a
flux dependence for the chemical sputtering at high flux, as well as
incident energy, incident angle, projectile/target mass ratios
dependencies, etc... Full references are given in the code. Manoj and I
tested these formulae extensively, even finding some mistakes and
smoothing out an unphysical resonance at threshold, so the degree of
confidence in them can be quite high. Care was taken that the formulae
vary continuously over the appropriate energy, flux and angle ranges.

The default parameters are for Graphite, but Manoj gave lists for
several over materials. The default model is a plate temperature
maintained at 300K, but this is changeable through the switches
'b2stbr_plate_temp' and 'b2stbr_plate_thick'. We pulled these numbers
out of thin air and the appropriate numbers for JET or AUG or ITER
parameters would be welcome.

This new code has been tested using my JET multi-fluid with drifts power
scan, going from Pcore of 2MW to 8MW and all runs are behaving nicely in
that respect. A "do no harm" test on runs without Carbon and with Carbon
but with Manoj's formulas turned off shows the expected behaviour (very
little change if any, due to the sheath acceleration being properly
accounted for by species).

Overall, we see that thermal evaporation and RES are completely
negligible, except where we have very high heat flux spikes (several
MW/m2). Manoj's formula for chemical sputtering tends to give about as
large carbon fluxes into the plasma that my old assumption of a
constant 1 to 2% level. The empirical physical sputtering yields are
comparable to the TRIM data. The fact that now multiply charged ions
feel a sheath acceleration multiplied by Za(is), while neutrals feel no
acceleration (as opposed to all species feeling a 3.0*Te energy
increase) changes where the sputtering comes from and which species
contribute most. Neutrals tend to now be below threshold and cause
little physical sputtering (but can still be dominant players for
chemical sputtering). The dominant cause of physical sputtering tends to
be C+3 and C+4 which have high incident energy because of the large
charge and are still present in large enough numbers in front of the
plates to carry significant particle influxes.

The new or modified code inputs are as such:
(Note the extended meaning of "b2stbr_sput_frc", "b2stbr_sput_phys", and
"b2stbr_sput_phys_col").

*    'b2stbr_sput_chem_model'   '0'                    Physics
*    'b2stbr_sput_phys_model'   '1'                    Physics
*    'b2stbr_sput_res'          '0.0'                  Physics
*    'b2stbr_therm_evap'        '0.0'                  Physics
*    'b2stbr_sput_dst'          '2'                    Physics
*    'b2stbr_sput_frc'          '0.0'                  Physics
*    'b2stbr_sput_phys'         '0.0'                  Physics
*    'b2stbr_sput_src'          '1'                    Physics
*    'b2stbr_sput_phys_col'     '3'                    Physics
*    'b2stbr_plate_temp'        '500.0'                Physics
*    'b2stbr_plate_thick'       '0.02'                 Physics
*    'b2stbr_plate_kfall'       '1130.0'               Physics
*    'b2stbr_plate_ka'          '122.0'                Physics
*    'b2stbr_vappr_a'           '-40181.0'             Physics
*    'b2stbr_vappr_b'           '14.80'                Physics
*    'b2stbr_stick_coef'        '0.4'                  Physics
*    Sputtering model switches. See the code in b2stbr and the
*    b2mod_sputter module for specific implementation details and
references.
*    The default values represent the case of Graphite plates.
*    Sput_src is the atomic number of the plasma species which cause
chemical
*    sputtering.
*    Sput_dst is the species index of the destination species produced
by
*    chemical sputtering, RES and thermal evaporation.
*    Sput_phys_model is a switch for choosing between the TRIM tables
*    (model 1) or an empirical formula (model 0). When TRIM data is not
*    available, the empirical formula is automatically used.
Extrapolations
*    of low and high energy ranges beyond the TRIM table data is done
using
*    the same physical dependencies as the empirical formula.
*    Sput_chem_model is a switch for the chemical sputtering model used.
*    If sput_chem_model.eq.0, the empirical formula is used.
*    If sput_chem_model.eq.1, a constant with a low energy cut-off is
used.
*    For model 0, sput_frc is a multiplier to the empirical formula,
while
*    for model 1, sput_frc is the constant chemical sputtering yield.
*    Sput_phys turns on physical sputtering when sput_phys.gt.0.0 and
*    contains a (real) multiplier for the physical sputtering rate
looked
*    up in the TRIM tables.
*    sput_phys_col indicates which column to use in the TRIM table; the
*    default (3) corresponds to 30 degrees incidence.  The columns are
for
*      0  15  30  45  55  65  75  80  85
*    degrees. This angle is also used in the empirical formula.
*    Plate_temp is the temperature (in Kelvin) of the COOLED end of the
*    divertor plates. The surface temperature is computed
self-consistently
*    (using a 1-D description) according to the incident heat fluxes
from
*    the plasma. The plate is assumed to have a thickness of
plate_thick,
*    measured in meters.
*    The plate material heat conductivity is fitted to an exponential,
where
*    the parameter plate_ka is a multiplier and the parameter
plate_kfall
*    is the exponential fall-off. Only Graphite is currently available.
*    Sput_res turns on radiation enhanced sublimation (RES) when .gt.0.0
and
*    is a multiplier to the RES rate.
*    Therm_evap turns on thermal evaporation when .gt.0.0 and is a
*    multiplier to the thermal evaporation rate.
*    The vapor pressure of the plate material is computed using a
parameter
*    fit, with the following examples (see b2mod_sputter for details):
*    (note that A and B are provided such that the vapor pressure is
*     given in Pascals)
*    Plate Material    |  A       |  B      |
*    ------------------+----------+---------|
*    Aluminum          | -16165   | 10.91   |
*    Beryllium         | -16720   | 11.61   |
*    Graphite          | -40181   | 14.80   |
*    Copper            | -17079   | 11.26   |
*    Molybdenum        | -33069   | 12.02   |
*    Titanium          | -23340   |  9.79   |
*    Tungsten          | -44485   | 12.74   |
*    Titanium Carbide  | -39117.9 | 15.23   |
*    Stainless Steel   | -14321.9 |  9.44   |
*    Stick_coef is the sticking coefficient of the material, and is
*    typically 0.6-0.9 for metals, 0.05 for C_3 molecules and 0.4 for C.

To avoid some nasty blowing up terms, there is a hidden parameter which
is the maximum allowed plate temperature (currently set to 2600 K) in
subroutine heatdiff from b2mod_sputter, to avoid reaching sublimation
temperatures, causing Carbon blooms and diverging thermal evaporation
fluxes.
Another adjustable parameter (for chemical sputtering) depends on doping
of the graphite plates, and we chose as the default a middle-range
value (in subroutine chmsput from b2mod_sputter), the argument being the
in AUG there should be some W that has wandered to the divertor. A
similar argument could be made in JET for B doping, for example.
       erel = 1.5e0_R8    ! erel =1.8 (for pure Graphite);
                          !      =1.5 (for Si,Ti,W doped graphite)
                          !      =1.2 (for B doped graphite)

