Hello David,

I've been busy again trying to get some more little ideas into the code.
Part of this is from discussions with Detlev, part with you at JET for
the EDGE2D benchmarking affort.

The main thrusts are:
- After some discussions with Detlev, Manoj and Ralf, we agreed that we
should include a backscattering model for non-recycling species, using
the TRIM data tables as our basis. I have now implemented this, where
backscattering will happen, by default, at all boundaries (except core
and island center) and for all non-hydrogenic species where both
particle and energy recycling coefficients are set to zero, against a
wall of the material given by "sput_dst". In practice, this means
backscattering of C on C (and also possibly some He on C). Overall, the
effect is quite small, and only adds a small fraction to the fluxes
already seen through sputtering. Energy backscattering is also included,
of course.

- I also discussed with Detlev the issue of Eirene-facelift. We agreed
that what B2 needs to pass to Eirene is the total drift velocities, so I
modified the code to do this (hence the version number change). Eirene
will also eventually want the electric potential, so I took some steps
towards that, but commenting out the crucial last step of actually
writing it to fort.44. This meant changes to BRAEIR.F and BRAEIR.H.
Detlev also said that Eirene-facelift was coming to completion, and that
the last issue to settle before it was ready to couple with SOLPS was to
re-unify the different versions of INFCOP he had into a single one. He
suggested that one should spend about two weeks with him on coupling
SOLPS and Eirene-facelift, but not before mid-april, as he'll be busy
with his lamp contract until then.

- Lastly, I also put some work into figuring out how to get the neutral
flux absorbed on the core boundary by Eirene back into B2 and feed it
back as an ion flux through the core boundary. I was not willing to use
the actual Eirene arrays for this, since this would require the user to
add non-standard diagnostics to the input.dat file, but noticed that
Kukushkin was already extracting this information and storing it in his
wldna, wldnm, wldra and wldrm arrays. With this, I was able to add a new
option 'eirene_ionizing_core' which, when set to '1', takes the total
flux for each atom and molecule crossing the core boundary and feeds it
back as a particle source of the appriopriate stripped ions (I assumed
molecules break up and atoms fully strip while in the core).
Unfortunately, the fluxes given are integrated over the whole surface,
so I could not do any "local" recycling, but rather did the refueling
using a constant flux density. However, one can argue that there is
sufficient redistribution in the core to make this a reasonable
assumption. Also, because the Kukushkin arrays changed meaning according
to whether the code was compiled with or without NO_FORT10 (AARGH!),
i.e. there were broken up per stratum or all elements just gave the
total value for all strata (again AARGH!), I had to assume the worst
case and could not do the refuelling per stratum, which also means that
this new option cannot be used simultaneously with Andrei's source
scaling. The code checks for this.

The files are in their usual location.

Cheers,

Xavier.

