I have added the following b2plot commands:
- "'ix' omp" : sets the position of the outer miplane to 'ix' (default
value is 'jxa')
- "'ix' imp" : sets the position of the inner midplane to 'ix' (default
value is 'jxi')
- "mmid" : flag for mapping to midplane
- "'iy' yref" : sets the reference flux surface to 'iy' (default value
is -2)

All these things work for the "fy" command, and also for "p*" where
"jxa" and "jxi" are used.
Ona can position the inner and outer midplanes at will with the "imp"
and "omp" commands, thus overwriting the defaults, which then allows one
to map a profile to any poloidal surface, including the plates.
When one activates the "mmid" switch, the profile is plotted using the
x-abscissae of the equivalent midplane flux tubes, but still only
plotting the flux tubes that exist at the chosen profile location (i.e.
not plotting insides of limiters etc). This is an "on/off" switch, very
much like "sep", with the default being "off". If it is turned on, the
graph title mentions "(mapped to midplane)", but the user must remember
where the midplane was. One could change this to "(mapped to ix =
",jxa,")", or use a different variable than "jxa", for example "ixref".
One can also now move the zero point of the abscissae. The default
remains the active separatrix for the poloidal cut considered, but one
can force the zero to be at a specific 'iy' location with the command
"'iy' yref". To turn this off, set "-2 yref". The reason the default for
this is not 'jsep' is that for disconnected double-nulls, 'jsep' is not
always the correct value (for example if looking into the private region
of the inactive X-point). I find that this can be useful, for example if
one wants to measure with respect to the island last closed flux surface
in a diverted island case (which is not the same at the separatrix), or
with respect to the outer separatrix in a disconnected double-null.
However, there is no mention on the graph of what is chosen as the
origin flux tube for the abscissae.

